Interesting.  I finally got to research this and run some tests.

PL/I(F) explicitly says the expression in a RETURN statement must be
an <element-expression>, meaning than structures and arrays cannot be
returned.

PL/I 1.1 generates a bunch of messages.  Enterprise PL/I 3.4 uses one:
"The STRUCTURE attribute is invalid as a RETURNS subattribute," which
is nicely to the point.

Kednos says "A return value can be any scalar...."

Multics PL/I says "If the <return value> is present, a <return
statement> is executed by evaluating the <return value> and promoting
its value to conform to the aggregate type specified in the <returns
attribute>...."  Aggregate type is element, array, or structure, so
this implies that function procedures can return aggregates, though
I'm not able to test this compiler.  This conforms to the PL/I
standard (full language and subset G).




