On Mar 16, 10:33=A0am, Peter_Fl...@Yahoo.com wrote:
>
> MulticsPL/I says "If the <return value> is present, a <return
> statement> is executed by evaluating the <return value> and promoting
> its value to conform to the aggregate type specified in the <returns
> attribute>...." =A0Aggregate type is element, array, or structure, so
> this implies that function procedures can return aggregates, though
> I'm not able to test this compiler. =A0This conforms to the PL/I
> standard (full language and subset G).

The Multics PL/I compiler supported structure returns.
It extended the ANSI standard to allow * extents in returns.
The Multics PL/I User's Guide as scanned by Al Kossow at
  http://www.bitsavers.org/pdf/honeywell/multics/AM83A_PL1refMan_Sep78.pdf
has an example on page 12-20:
  A1: proc(X) returns (01 dim(*), 02 float, 02 fixed dec(8));
    dcl 01 X(*), 02 num float, 02 x fixed dec(8;
    return (X+1);
  end;
which returns an array of structures.  When called, A1 determines
the size of its input from the argument descriptor, allocates a
temporary,
creates the result of the expression in the temporary, and then uses
a return operator that temporarily extends the stack frame of the
caller
to include the temporary value.


