Hi Bill!

I know you from the comp.os.cpm newsgroup.  I lurk here and os 
comp.os.cpm, too.
The PL/I about which they are writing is IBM mainframe PL/I -- Probably 
z/OS but could be as early as OS/MVS or OS/390 or even VM/CMS or z/VM.

There are PL/I subset G compilers available for free from Digital 
Research which work on CP/M, CP/M-86 and PC DOS 1.0.  Because of a 
change in PC DOS 1.1 and later (also MS DOS 1.1 and later), the end of 
file is not properly recognized making the DOS compiler less than 
useful.  It does still work under Windows XP, although it still has the 
end of file problem.  I made a stab at correcting the end-of-file 
problem many years ago, but was unsuccessful.  I did manage to 
disassemble and decompile the libraries, so finding and correcting the 
end of file problem ought to be possible.

The death of PL/I is exaggerated, but neither IBM nor Liant are doing 
much to make it modern, in the Object Oriented sense or available in the 
financial sense.  There certainly haven't been many changes to the 
language since the IBM PL/I optimizing compiler was created.  Please, no 
flame-wars, I know the enterprise compiler is different and that it is 
available under Windows, but the language definition is substantially 
the same with few extensions since the optimizing compiler.

I happen to enjoy programming in PL/I, even the DOS and  CP/M-86 
versions.  I regret having no access to a usable PL/I compiler for DOS 
or Windows.  I find that thinking in PL/I is much easier than other 
languages.  I resort to writing a program in PL/I and then translating 
it to C to get the job done.  And making C do the same thing PL/I does 
is not a trivial task.

I look forward to the Gnu version or any other version which we can 
build which will work under Windows and/or Linux.

I hope you find this "one person's take on PL/I" to be helpful.  And 
thanks for helping keep the old software alive on all of your great 
websites.

Richard Brady

