Shmuel (Seymour J.) Metz wrote:
> In <93m8h.21742$fz1.9263@newsfe15.phx>, on 11/20/2006
>    at 10:01 AM, "Donald L. Dobbs" <donaldldobbs@cox.net> said:
> 
>> I agree that when PL/I was introduced on the S/360 it produced slow, 
>> bloated code.
> 
> I understand that PL/I on Multics did not, unless you count EPL.
Probably true, but it came along a little later.  Also, PL/I (F) was 
written in S/360 ALC and took a huge amount of manhours whereas 
Multics was written in a higher-level language (I think). This gave 
them more time to concentrate on better design and fewer keystrokes.
> 
>> Although, I have to confess that Digital Research PL/I-86 generates 
>> more efficient code than C and I use it on x86 platforms.
> 
> Wasn't it missing part of the language? I never tried it because I was
> too scarred by DR C, which left me unwilling to trust any compiler
> from DR.
The only DR products I use are DR Display Manager and DR PL/I-86 which 
were completely homegrown. Never tried to use any other DR products 
which were originally purchased from others (Turbo C, Business Basic, 
Pascal, etc.) for the same reason you cite.  Display Manager is 
extremely useful for screenwork in pure DOS environments that use 
character-generated CRTs rather than bit-mapped CRTs.

PL/I-86 purports to be PL/I subset G, but I suspect it is actually a 
subset of subset G because at the time it was developed the 
microprocessors were still essentially 16-bit architecture.  For example,
    dcl x fixed bin (15);
was legal, but
    dcl x fixed bin (31);
was not supported.
If I needed an integer larger than 32767 I had to resort to
    dcl x fixed decimal (12);
or something like that (12 is just for talking purposes and not the 
decimal limit). And the generated code actually made use of the Intel 
DAA instruction and performed the computations in packed decimal.

The reason PL/I-86 is so efficient is that the late Dr. Gary Kildall 
did his PhD thesis on compiler optimization.  Some time later Byte 
Magazine published a shoot-out of all the available microprocessor 
compilers of the time and DR PL/I beat out every other one in both 
speed of execution and smallness of code.

In the interest of full disclosure, I have to admit that DR PL/I has a 
runtime bug.  You cannot repeatedly close and reopen the same file 
(within the same session) with consistent results.  Someone came along 
later, decompiled the runtime and devised a fix.  Unfortunately, the 
fix made the problem worse so I went back to the original runtime.

Because of the microprocessor limitations at the time, the PL/I- 
generated code must fit in a 64K byte page and all the variables must 
be confined to a (different) 64K byte page.  However, the bundled 
linkage editor supports overlays nested up to 7 levels deep. In a 
modern PC with lots of RAM you can create a RAM disk and the thing 
screams right along with no noticeable delays. I rarely have to do 
this because the code is so compact that 64K holds a very large 
program. (In reality, most HDDs nowadays have large enough caches 
and/or buffers that resorting to a RAM disk isn't necessary.)

Other than that, it is a rather nice implementation and supports 
enough of the language to do just about anything you'd want to in a PC 
environment.

For example:  I few years ago I inherited the job from a client of 
debugging and fixing some M68xx firmware that ran in a real-time 
device.  Luckily the source code was available.  It was obvious from 
the dates and styles of the comments that I was the fifth programmer 
to touch the code as it evolved over a number of years. The bug had 
eluded prior attempts and the customer was stuck with rebooting the 
machine at least once every other day (no, Micro$oft wasn't involved). 
  I wrote a cross reference program in PL/I-86 to scan the source 
since this was not a feature of the M68xx assembler I had to use. The 
program not only kept track of variable usage but also produced a list 
of the "come froms".  The M68xx firmware source code was about 85 
printed pages and the cross-referenced output was over 120 pp.  From 
the time I hit RETURN on the DOS command line prompt to start the 
process until it was finished was about 0.7 seconds.  During that time 
the PL/I application was loaded; it opened and scanned the source 
twice; did the computations (sorting); and produced the spooled 
output. Now for the kicker -- the microprocessor runs at 166 MHz !!! 
When I run the same setup on a 1GHz processor it's done before I can 
get my finger off the ENTER key.

It's because of this kind of performance (and simplicity) that I just 
can't get too excited about OO, or inaccessible CVs, or reserved words 
(and a dozen other 'features' of languages that bombard this DG).
> 
>> But, I have to resort to assembly or C on other platforms such as 
>> M68xx because I am not aware of any PL/I-86 for those architectures.
> 
> LPI?
Haven't looked at LPI for 68xx specifically.  I think the last time I 
visited their web page (for x86) their stuff was rather pricey. 
Usually the client is reluctant to invest in my tools.
> 


