Governor wrote:

> We all know that PL/I supports various base, scale and precision
> combinations for arithmetic data types.
> 
> One thing that has always puzzled me, is the real-world need for binary
> fractions and binary float?
> 
> Also why the need or perceived need for binary integers that are arbitrary
> bits in length?
> 
> I mean who ever really needs:
> 
> 1. bin(23);
> 2. bin(13);
> 3. bin(10,2)
> 
> etc.
> 
> In my view this is one of the least useful aspects of PL/I and it imposes
> a significant burden of the implementation.
> 
> I see no real down side (for a practical PLI implementation in NT) to
> restricting binary to
> 
> 7, 15, 31, 63 bits
> and not supporting fractional bits.
> 
> Thoughts?

ANSI Subset G allows only binary integers (scale=0), and it seems to get 
along all right.  There's not too much overhead to supporting other than 
register sizes - the only time you have to worry about it is if SIZE is 
enabled.  BINARY FLOAT makes sense, since it's the natural Intel FLOAT 
format, it's DECIMAL FLOAT that needs to be simulated.  What are you 
doing about DECIMAL FIXED?  FLOAT data is widely used for computation, 
including, IIRC, graphics.



