Peter Flass wrote:

> Governor wrote:
> 
>> We all know that PL/I supports various base, scale and precision
>> combinations for arithmetic data types.
>>
>> One thing that has always puzzled me, is the real-world need for binary
>> fractions and binary float?
>> [...]
> ANSI Subset G allows only binary integers (scale=0), and it seems to get 
> along all right.  There's not too much overhead to supporting other than 
> register sizes - the only time you have to worry about it is if SIZE is 
> enabled.  BINARY FLOAT makes sense, since it's the natural Intel FLOAT 
> format, it's DECIMAL FLOAT that needs to be simulated.  What are you 
> doing about DECIMAL FIXED?  FLOAT data is widely used for computation, 
> including, IIRC, graphics.
> 
FLOAT BINARY is crucial.  I'm not so sure about FLOAT DECIMAL; as with
fractional FIXED BINARY, I've never used it nor do I remember having
seen it used but my experience is somewhat limited.

There is an issue with FLOAT BINARY on IBM 360s and their successors
that used a hexadecimal, rather than binary, base.  The reason you'll
see a lot of declarations of the form FLOAT BINARY (21) and FLOAT BINARY
(53) is that the 360 used 6 hexadecimal digits (24 bits) for single
precision floating point and 14 hexadecimal digits (56 bits) for double
precision floating point.  However, when a single precision hexadecimal
fraction is normalized, the leading digit can be any of {1, 2, 3, ...,
E, F}.  If the leading hexadecimal digit is 1, the three leading bits of
the binary representation are zero so the number of significant binary
digits is only 21 (24 - 3).  While it's possible to have as many as 24
significant binary digits, depending on the leading hexadecimal digit,
only 21 significant binary digits can be guaranteed.

Similarly with double precision floating point, the maximum number of
binary digits is 56, if the leading hexadecimal digit is 8 or greater,
but the maximum number that can be guaranteed is 53 (56 - 3).

Thus, a declaration of the form FLOAT BINARY (24) on an IBM 360 would
require the PL/I compiler to use double precision.  Note, as with FIXED
BINARY, for every FLOAT BINARY precision use the machine's smallest
"native" floating point precision that is greater than or equal to the
specified precision.

Note the IEEE floating point representation is clever with regard to the
leading binary digit.  That is, it uses a binary radix (rather than the
360's hexadecimal) so, as long as a value can be represented in
normalized format, every bit is significant.  However, IEEE formats take
advantage of the fact that the leading binary digit of the normalized
representation is always "1" (except when the value being represented is
zero) and omits it from the representation.  Thus, the values 1E0, 2E0,
4E0, 8E0, etc. would be represented by appropriate exponent and sign
fields, but the mantissa would be zero (because the leading "1" bit is
implied).  For example, see
http://www.math.byu.edu/~schow/work/IEEEFloatingPoint.htm .  Thus, if
the single precision floating point representation in storage has 23
bits for the mantissa, then it corresponds to FLOAT BINARY (24).
Similarly, if the double precision IEEE floating point representation in
storage has 52 bits for the mantissa, then it corresponds to FLOAT
BINARY (53).


