I've never written a whole compiler for it.  I joined a PL/I compiler
project after it was mostly complete and much of the work I did did not
require referring to the Standard.  But I did use it to correct the
implementation of the PL/I F-format for that project.  I found it handy 
to use several bookmarks (and a few fingers) concurrently in order to
switch among the various relevant sections of the Standard.  I'm not
sure whether my employer used the Standard to implement our compiler,
but we all referred to it to resolve ambiguities and whenever a customer
claimed to have found an instance of non-standard behavior.

I've read several ANSI language standards (COBOL, MUMPS, FORTRAN 1966,
Fortran 77, Pascal, PL/I), some all the way through (the Fortran and
Pascal Standards).  There are a few features of the ANSI PL/I Standard
that seem unique to it.

First, it is the most complete of those Standards.  That is, there are
very few circumstances in which behavior is unspecified and left up to
the whim of the developer (e.g., minimum number of trips through
DO-loop, completeness of specifications for conversion between types of
various precisions, etc.) -- whereas other "standards" (especially 
Pascal) seemed to use the words "undefined" and "implementation defined" 
a lot and still others just didn't mention such behavior (FORTRAN 1966 
specified that the end value of a DO-loop had to be greater than or 
equal to the start value but didn't specify whether it should be enforced).

Second, great care seems to have been taken to define each concept in
only one place.  Except for a relatively small percentage (though a
large number) of basic definitions, all concepts are defined in terms of
other definitions in the Standard.  Thus, in order to understand the
definition of F-format, for example, it's necessary to keep referring to
the original locations in the Standard of the transitive closure of
definitions of the terms used to define it -- or to know those
definitions already.  This makes it a little difficult to use, but
guarantees that each term has only one meaning wherever it's used.


