COBOL has a large list of reserved words, that, as I understand 
(never having tried) a COBOL programmer must always keep nearby.

PL/I authors, knowing about this problem and that PL/I would have
many features a given program would not use specifically so
that users wouldn't have to remember them all.

It might be, though, that lazy compiler writers didn't follow that.

It may also be that subset G doesn't have that feature, though that
would be surprising.  Remember,

if if=then then then=else; else else=if;

And of course everyone here knows that Fortran doesn't have
reserved words (unless that changed recently).

