In article <3B35DA43.4A5E2752@yahoo.com>, Peter Flass
<peter_flass@yahoo.com> wrote:

>PL/I(D) woud run (walk?) on a 32K machine.  Supervisors then were
>running 6-8K so that gave it 24K.  Amazing.  Bill Gates couldn't write
>"Hello world" to run in 24K.

IBM used letter codes to refer to the (core) memory size on 360s, with
a given letter implying the machine had 2^(letter-A+1) KB of memory.
The compilers at a given "design level" had to fit in less than this,
to leave room for the operating system.

So 'D' meant that the compiler ran in a 16K machine. With a DOS/360
non-multiprogramming supervisor of 6K, that required the compiler to
run in the remaining 10K. (This was on a 2311-based system. IIRC, for
2314's, it took 12K.) The D-level PL/I and COBOL compilers, assembler,
linkage editor, sort/merge, and DOS utilities were all designed to run
in a 10K area -- the equivalent of slightly over 5 pages in a printed
dump. (I don't remember a D-level FORTRAN. I think the lowest level
was E-level, i.e., 32K machine.)

- Jim Saum


