In article <3b2bfb60$6$fuzhry$mr2ice@va.news.verio.net>, "Shmuel (Seymour
J.) Metz" <spamtrap@library.lspace.org.invalid> wrote:

>In <9foka4$fh@gap.cco.caltech.edu>, on 06/07/2001
>   at 07:22 PM, gah@ugcs.caltech.edu (glen herrmannsfeldt) said:
>
>>Reference in the sense that it was first, the one
>>that the PL/I Language Reference was written for, 
>
>AFAIK that manual had no relevance to anything beyond F.

The OS/360 PL/I (F) LRM documented only the F-level language. There
was a separate manual called something like "PL/I DOS Subset Language"
(?) that documented the language implemented in the PL/I (D) compiler
that ran under DOS/360. And as mentioned previously in this thread,
the language subset supported by the D compiler was not the same as
the much later ANSI Subset G that was implemented on various non-IBM
platforms a decade or so later.

I always thought the impressive thing about the D compiler was that it
ran on a 16K machine, where some of the memory was taken by the DOS
supervisor.

- Jim Saum


