Hi,

"Donald L. Dobbs" wrote:
> 
> 386sx wrote:
> >
> > "Ron Alexander" <rcalex@home.com> wrote:
> >
> > > And in Stratus PL1 if the strings are declared char varying it is
> > > c=a+b;
> > >
> > > Why do C bigots not like char varying? Is it because they like to waste
> > > cpu cycles looking for the 0x00 terminator?
> >
> > Do you mean to say that there is no 0x00 terminator behind the scenes in
> > PL1? So how then are strings terminated?
> 
> If the string is declared as CHAR (nn) then the length of the string is
> known to the compiler and to any subsequent references [where nn is the
> specified length in bytes].
> 
> If the string is declared as CHAR (nn) VARYING then nn is the maximum
> length of the string and the "dope vector" [at least that is what it was
> called back in the 60's] is a 2-byte value with the current length of
> the string. The actual storage required for the string is 2 bytes longer
> than the specified length.
> 
> The extra two bytes had to be accounted for when passing varying length
> strings as parameters to other languages.  I am not current on some of
> this but I think newer implementations of PL/I now allow for string
> declarations that are more compatible with other languages such as C,
> etc.
> 
> Also, in the original PL/I subset G implementation for CP/M and DOS the
> "dope vector" was just one byte -- hence a CHAR VARYING was limited to
> 255 bytes while the original IBM Level F allowed strings as long as
> either 32767 or 65535 (I don't recall if they treated the length as an
> unsigned 16-bit or a signed 16-bit number).
> 
> IMHO the extra two bytes is a very small price to pay to avoid looping
> through a long string looking for the 0-byte terminator.

It also allows you to actually use the '0' value to send padding
(timing) bytes out to peripheral devices that need them.

> 
> >
> > --
> > 386
> >
> > Just the FAQ Jack:
> > http://www.eskimo.com/~scs/C-faq/top.html


