If by the ANSI Spec you refer to X3.53-1976, I just happen to have a copy of
it here.  This is the original ANSI spec for the full PL/I language.  Some
vendors never implemented this version, and some vendors implemented the
so-called Subset G PL/I standard, which came out a few years later.

Paragraph 1.2.1.4, titled "Expression Evaluation" says, in part, that an
implementation may deviate from the strict order of evaluation defined by
various operations in 4 respects. (1) It need not raise all of the
interrupts that strict evaluation would raise, (2) It need not raise the
interrupts in the same order as strict evaluation, (3) It may evaluate an
expression, value-reference, variable-reference, or target-reference by
evaluating its contained expressions in any order, provided that the
association of operands with operators is maintained, (4) It need not
evaluate an expression, variable-reference, or target-reference if it can
determine the result without evaluating it except when the result depends on
the value returned by a contained procedure-function-reference (it has to
invoke the function). Further, if it does not evaluate an expression, it
need not raise any interrupts that may have been raised.

What all this says is that if the compiler can guarantee that the result it
produces is consistent with the definition of the PL/I language, it need not
evaluate an entire expression.  Further, it may employ an optimizer that
rearranges the order of evaluation to some other, more convenient order than
that written by the programmer. The optimizer may combine common expressions
when it can demonstrate that the meaning of the program has not changed. If
these optimizations eliminate interrupts (aka conditions), that's ok.
However, while the standard doesn't say so explicitly, except by silence,
every compiler I've worked on has also been careful not to raise any
conditions that would not have otherwise been raised. (E.g., it won't hoist
a divide out of a loop if it might produce a zerodivide condition).

Note that this restriction applies to the compiler or interpreter of PL/I.
This is of little use to the PL/I programmer.  Unlike in C where you can be
assured that the compiler will never evaluate the right-hand side of the
short-circuit logical operators (double-and, double-or) when the left-hand
side forces the final result, in PL/I you can never make such an assumption.
The language defines the result of the AND and OR operators in terms of
complete evaluation. It gives the compilers the freedom to use incomplete
evaluation but the compilers are not required to use it. Therefore, all PL/I
programs must be coded such that the entire expression can be evaluated.
This comes up from time to time in our shop when we get an experienced C
programmer and teach him or her PL/I; we have to stress that they use
nested-if statements, not C-style Boolean logic, to test a pointer for
non-null and then reference thru it.

I have worked on, and used, both the Honeywell Multics PL/I compiler (which
implemented the full ANSI PL/I language) and the Stratus PL/I compiler
(which implements the Subset G PL/I language), and both of them follow the
ANSI Standard in exactly this way. If the optimizer is not used (say, for
debugging), the entire expression is evaluated. If the optimizer is used at
the appropriate optimization level (say, for production), some expressions
are only partially evaluated.

By the way, this means it is incorrect to say that the ANSI PL/I Standard
requires that the entire expression be evaluated. What is requires is that
the result the compiler provides must be the same result that would be
provided if the entire expression is evaluated.

Hope this helps.

PG
--
