I would expect them to be mutually exclusive in the syntax. They are
in VDL, I believe. If somebody has a copy of the "Vienna phonebook"
(Shmuel seems to have stuff like that) perhaps they could check this
for me. The PUT statement is old enough to appear in the early
definitions, so it should simply be a matter of decoding the VDL.

More than this, a programmer would expect such an error to be
identified in a syntax check only compilation. If such erroneous code
parsed correctly under syntax check and then failed in code generation
the programmer would be rightly furious.

r>  > Using your productions these can recurse to join one another,
r>  >but using more than 1 is actually invalid.
r> 
r>  >Similarly, your productions allow FILE() to occur twice
r>  or more. Likewise for the other control options.
r> 
r> FILE?  I didn't include a FILE specification.

It was in the "etc." part for control options, I would have inferred,
since FILE() would usually be coded as one of the first group of
"control options". However, all the control options could be
duplicated and still parse correctly. Thus PUT SKIP(2) SKIP(3); would be
syntactically correct using your productions.

r> The options in PUT statements are mainly of the form
r> 
r> PUT <identifier> <list of things>
r> or
r> PUT <identifier> <list of things> <identifier> <list of things>
r> etc,
r> (and the <list of things may be missing)
r> which can be handled well in BNF.

Again, you would allow SKIP or LINE to appear twice or more, and to
appear with each other when mutually exclusive.

Also, the <list of things> can be <empty> for some <identifier> (e.g.
SKIP, PAGE, DATA) but not for others (e.g. FILE, LINE, LIST). The
above does not address that, but it is of fundamental importance for
syntax checking. However, this is easily dealt with in BNF; the
permutations are the things that make BNF cumbersome.

But the issue is that after the PUT the keyword-introduced items can
appear in any order. For this BNF is clumsy, at best. With a grammar
the size of PL/I it is just too unwieldy.

r> There's one exception, namely, with an EDIT list, where the
r> data list can be followed by a format list, and then by another
r> data list and format list etc.

That's actually quite easily dealt with, since it is simply a
recursion. You cannot place any other options between pairs of I/O
lists and edit patterns.

E.g., assuming left-recursion,

 <edit option> ::= EDIT <list_and_pattern_pairs>
 <list_and_pattern_pairs> ::= <list_pattern_pair> |
                 <list_and_pattern_pairs> <list_pattern_pair>
 <list_pattern_pair> ::= (io_list) (edit_pattern)

This should even force the programmer to supply at least one I/O list
and edit pattern.

Regards

Dave
<Team PL/I>

