In a message dated 09-11-97, Eric Jackson said to All about Re: Bnf For Pli
Subset G

EJ>Two points:

EJ>1. BNF was in use long before XPL.  I believe it was used to define the
EJ>Algol language, but I'm not sure this was the first use.

Yes, it was an upshot of ALGOL 58 (the preliminary draft) and was used to
define ALGOL 60.

EJ>2. XPL looked like PL/I, but it was not PL/I.  Its syntax was reduced so
EJ>that it could be described by an LAR grammar like BNF can describe.

Indeed, McKeeman, et al., were so enamoured with BNF that the XPL system
included an analyser to permit compiler writers to enter raw BNF for the
grammar they wanted to compile.

EJ>ken koswener  <big-bird@ix.netcom.com> wrote in article
EJ><5ut6rl$6fm@sjx-ixn9.ix.netcom.com>...
> >What makes you think BNF is an adequate tool for defining PL/I?
> >Dave
> 
> because it is, and has been since the late 60's when it was introduced
> along with the XPL system.

The BNF for PL/I would be horrendous. Just consider the PUT statement for
printing:

   PUT FILE(...) SKIP(...) EDIT(<io_list>) (<edit_pattern>);
   PUT SKIP(...) EDIT(<io_list>) (<edit_pattern>) FILE(...);
   PUT FILE(...) EDIT(<io_list>) (<edit_pattern>) SKIP(...);
   PUT EDIT(<io_list>) (<edit_pattern>) FILE(...) SKIP(...);
   PUT EDIT(<io_list>) (<edit_pattern>) SKIP(...) FILE(...);

etc., etc., all mean the same thing but require separate productions because
of the different orderings. And we haven't introduced PAGE or LIST or DATA,
let alone repetitions of the I/O list and edit pattern pairs. And then there
is the GET statement too.

Of course, these are small compared to DECLARE.

Anybody who uses BNF to attempt to describe PL/I needs a serious rethink.

Regards

Dave
<Team PL/I>
