In article <4iur66$161m@usenetw1.news.prodigy.com>, davidsen@tmr.com (bill davidsen) writes:
>We have free compilers for virtually every language known available
>for "free" UNIX implementations like Linux. Is there no PL/I, at
>least subset G, around? Sure would be nice to have a practical home
>system on a realistic operating system.
>
Because it's very difficult to make it work correctly, to say nothing
of making the compiled code run quickly.  Things like:
	data conversion of PICTURE to anything.
	non-local goto's with a target of an eternally visible
		label which is in a different compilation module
		(and different procedure)
	signal handling mechanisms which deal with non-local goto's
		correctly.
	passing an entry variable for a routine (which is nested inside
		the current lexical/static scope level) to an up-level
		dynamic scope.

And that's ignoring all of the features available in mainframe PL/I
which aren't specified in the ANSI language.  (I was a developer for
LPI/Liant for a number of years).

