I agree.

However the term 'Subset G' is usually taken to refer to the language
specified by ANSI X3.74-1981 a very limited definition.

To this day many assume that Subset G is this.

Subset G 1981 is (rightly) seen as a rather limited and restrictive
definition of a PL/I subset. The 1987 specification is however much
more powerful.

For example I beleive that Stratus's PL/I compiler for VOS is an
implementation of the 1981 standard, and lacks many of the more
powerful features defined in 1987 standard.

Some of the fatures in the 1987 standard, that are not in the 1981
are:

REFER
AREA and OFFSET types
INITIAL for automatic variables
DO LOOP for indefinite looping
SELECT groups
PACKAGE

etc

I was simply making it clear that ANSI X3.74-1987 is not to be seen as
the same thing as 'Subset G' because this Subset is almost always
taken to mean the 1981 standard, despite the fact that both standards
are titled Subset G.

I dont think that any implementation of X3.74-1987 actually exists,
please let me know if this isnt the case.

Hugh


