In article <5rvn0f$2lq$1@hermes.is.co.za> "Peter Hamilton-Scott" 
<hamscott@icon.co.za> wrote: 
>I want to use a value in a picture dcl. Trouble is I'm not sure how to 
>define the picture such that it takes these rules into account: 
> 
>1) If the value is <0 display it like -100. 
>2) If the value is =0 display nothing (spaces). 
>3) If the value is >0 display it like 100. 
> 
>Ive tried pictures like '----9' (rule 1) and like 'zzzzz' (Rule 2) and like 
>'zzzz9' (Rule 3). The closest I come to all three could be a compromise 
>like '----z' but the compiler barks at me for being an idiot! 
>True, I may be, but can someone give me some advice on how I'd do this. 
> 
>PS. Please reply to PeterH@nedcor.co.za  

Here is the VOS PL/I program to accomplish this task, along with its output: 

    1  t_pic: 
    2       procedure; 
    3   
    4       call test (-100); 
    5       call test (0); 
    6       call test (+100); 
    7       return; 
    8   
    9  test: 
   10       procedure (v); 
   11   
   12  dcl  v bin (15); 
   13  dcl  p picture '-----'; 
   14   
   15       /* assign the numeric value to a picture, then 
   16          translate spaces to dots to prove that the 
   17          picture is working as expected. */ 
   18   
   19       p = v; 
   20       put list ('|' || translate (p, '.', ' ') || '|'); 
   21       put skip; 
   22   
   23       end test; 
   24   
   25       end t_pic; 

!t_pic 
|.-100|  
|.....|  
|..100|  

Pictures are documented on pages 4-16 thru 4-20 in R009-02, the 
VOS PL/I Language Manual.  Pay close attention to the 
documentation of "drifting fields" on page 4-19.  This trick of 
a picture consisting entirely of a sign character will work with 
"-", "+", "s", or "$".  And if the dollar-sign isn't the proper 
currency symbol for your locale, the translate builtin can be 
used to replace it with the appropriate Latin Alphabet #1 
character. 

The compiler barfed at "----z" because a picture with a drifting 
field (the "----") is not allowed to contain or be preceded by 
9, y, t, i, r, z, or *.  Got that?  (If you think the VOS PL/I 
manual is complicated in this respect, check out the 
create-numeric-picture operation in X3.74, which is where the 
ANSI PL/I General Purpose Subset standard defines pictures; they 
are quite complex). 

PG 
